<div id="review_2334829492" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2334829492" />
    <a title="Nigeyb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10301421-nigeyb"><img alt="Nigeyb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593065725p2/10301421.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2334829492?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nigeyb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nigeyb" href="/user/show/10301421-nigeyb">Nigeyb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2334829492" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7405080970870943280">&apos;<a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1271104.The_Road_Home' title='The Road Home by Rose Tremain' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Road Home</a>&apos; is another profound and moving novel by the always reliable <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4183.Rose_Tremain' title='Rose Tremain' rel='nofollow noopener'>Rose Tremain</a>. <br/><br/>How does Rose Tremain create such flawed but compelling characters? <br/><br/>And think her way into their mindset, and evoke their inner lives so convincingly? <br/><br/>In this instance, the central character is Lev, an unemployed father from eastern Europe, who travels to London to seek work. Through Lev&apos;s eyes, we get a chillingly accurate view of London through the eyes of a newly arrived, modern-day economic migrant, and</span>
  <span id="freeText7405080970870943280" style="display:none">'<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1271104.The_Road_Home" title="The Road Home by Rose Tremain" rel="nofollow noopener">The Road Home</a>' is another profound and moving novel by the always reliable <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4183.Rose_Tremain" title="Rose Tremain" rel="nofollow noopener">Rose Tremain</a>. <br><br>How does Rose Tremain create such flawed but compelling characters? <br><br>And think her way into their mindset, and evoke their inner lives so convincingly? <br><br>In this instance, the central character is Lev, an unemployed father from eastern Europe, who travels to London to seek work. Through Lev's eyes, we get a chillingly accurate view of London through the eyes of a newly arrived, modern-day economic migrant, and it's not pretty. <br><br>Gradually, Lev gets himself on his feet and so begins a peripatetic, occasionally comic, often traumatic, journey through London, which Tremain uses to illustrate broader themes.<br><br>Finally, after many ups and downs, Lev develops a compelling vision to sustain him, as yet another splendid novel by Rose Tremain wends towards its moving and satisfying climax.<br><br>4/5<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1327903370l/1271104.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
  <a data-text-id="7405080970870943280" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


