  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/40978894" />
    <a title="Jon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1828558-jon"><img alt="Jon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1300151668p2/1828558.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/40978894?book_show_action=true">Dec 26, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jon" href="/user/show/1828558-jon">Jon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/2626618-the-road-home">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer40978894" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10311283251834991395">Am writing this in post read glow. I love Tremain, i definately need to read more. Music and Silence was such a treasure of a book for me, and this one so totally different it threw me for a bit. The setting of a gritty and real London, people struggling to get by, cold bitter and grim was a little close to home. But once that feeling passed I had to acknowledge that It was good to be reading about real life, current issues and struggles. I think Tremains real gift in this was her characterisati</span>
  <span id="freeText10311283251834991395" style="display:none">Am writing this in post read glow. I love Tremain, i definately need to read more. Music and Silence was such a treasure of a book for me, and this one so totally different it threw me for a bit. The setting of a gritty and real London, people struggling to get by, cold bitter and grim was a little close to home. But once that feeling passed I had to acknowledge that It was good to be reading about real life, current issues and struggles. I think Tremains real gift in this was her characterisation and dialogue, she had people from all walks of life's accents down pat. I love that, when you can hear them play out in your head and smile at how spot on she is. There were plenty of light moments amongst the struggle. One of my favourite things was the chapter headings. e.g '2.5 meters of steel draining top', always a little obscure but you just knew those few words would be something pivotal coming up at any moment as you were reading. Its a pretty graphic book, with a fair bit of course language and sex so if your easily offended by that you might flinch, but it seemed fitting for the characters. Tremain number 2 for me has definatley confirmed her as one of those authors id just pick up and buy now.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10311283251834991395" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


