<div id="review_2587750935" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2587750935" />
    <a title="Robert Day" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13307338-robert-day"><img alt="Robert Day" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442972150p2/13307338.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2587750935?book_show_action=true">Nov 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Day" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Day" href="/user/show/13307338-robert-day">Robert Day</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781409078647" href="/book/show/17428070-the-road-home">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2587750935" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2420603037897416911">A thoughtful book and one that is powerfully written.<br/>By thoughtful, I mean that the author seems to have done some good research into experience of people living in Eastern Europe and the reasons why they come to work in Western Europe. It&apos;s a kind and insightful portrait she has painted of Lev.<br/>By powerfully written I mean that she writes in such a way that the emotions of the reader are engaged in the events of the story. As a consequence, what happens to Lev is felt by the reader. There&apos;s a do</span>
  <span id="freeText2420603037897416911" style="display:none">A thoughtful book and one that is powerfully written.<br />By thoughtful, I mean that the author seems to have done some good research into experience of people living in Eastern Europe and the reasons why they come to work in Western Europe. It's a kind and insightful portrait she has painted of Lev.<br />By powerfully written I mean that she writes in such a way that the emotions of the reader are engaged in the events of the story. As a consequence, what happens to Lev is felt by the reader. There's a downside to that: much of his experience is of sadness and disappointment. He is worried much of the time. He cares for and thinks deeply about the people around him, and this seeps into the mind of the reader. I was affected.<br />Am I allowed to comment on the ending? I don't know this author and I don't know if she is in the habit of writing happy endings. And so I don't know whether to tell you about it or not. Maybe you should read it yourself. All I'll say is that it's worth the journey.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2420603037897416911" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


